{"version":2,"kind":"Article","sha256":"9b04bd08fdd463ed78e7ef8668f72b72719164c072731457855b3b4a17bf55b1","slug":"blog.2018.free-labor-partners","location":"/blog/2018/free-labor-partners.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Open communities need to be partners, not sources of free labor","tags":["open communities","open culture","sustainability"],"date":"2018-12-05","content_includes_title":false,"authors":[{"id":"chris","nameParsed":{"literal":"Chris Holdgraf","given":"Chris","family":"Holdgraf"},"name":"Chris Holdgraf","orcid":"0000-0002-2391-0678","affiliations":["affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0","affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"],"url":"https://chrisholdgraf.com","github":"choldgraf","twitter":"choldgraf"}],"github":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io","affiliations":[{"name":"2i2c","url":"https://2i2c.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-0"},{"name":"Project Jupyter","url":"https://jupyter.org","id":"affiliations-myst-generated-uid-1"}],"abbreviations":{"LF":"The Linux Foundation","JF":"The Jupyter Foundation","JEC":"Jupyter Executive Council","JFB":"The Jupyter Foundation Board","SSC":"Software Steering Council","OSPO":"Open Source Program Office"},"numbering":{"title":{"offset":2}},"source_url":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io/blob/main/blog/2018/free-labor-partners.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/choldgraf/choldgraf.github.io/edit/main/blog/2018/free-labor-partners.md","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"free-labor-partners.md","url":"/build/free-labor-partners-943d8b6f9cf67838f78ef610d242ece8.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":16,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In the last couple of years, we’ve seen an increasing number of organizations start to\nspawn products that take a largely open stack (e.g., the SciPy ecosystem) and wrap\nit in a thin layer of proprietary/custom interface + infrastructure.\nOn the face of it, this isn’t a problem - I really want people to be able to\nmake money using the open source stack - however, there is a big caveat. When you look\nat the work that those organizations have done over time, you often see a pretty thin trail\nof contributions ","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"tfuA6hKBTF"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"back","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"ziVBfZfHBH"}],"key":"DZs2WToANO"},{"type":"text","value":" to those open source projects.","position":{"start":{"line":10,"column":1},"end":{"line":10,"column":1}},"key":"LaW7RCw1Bg"}],"key":"ToAwmEFko7"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":20,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I’d argue that using an open community’s software without contributing back is straight-up\nexploitative (legal, sure, but still exploitative), and we should think about ways to\nsuppress this kind of behavior. This post is a collection of thoughts on that topic.","position":{"start":{"line":18,"column":1},"end":{"line":18,"column":1}},"key":"RvsFjQUZ8M"}],"key":"TmMgRhv9Z0"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"But first....","position":{"start":{"line":22,"column":1},"end":{"line":22,"column":1}},"key":"c80LxkznMf"}],"key":"OXo0UW5TTm"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Why should I care whether I’m being a “good citizen in the open community”?","position":{"start":{"line":24,"column":1},"end":{"line":24,"column":1}},"key":"VDhQnoSHC4"}],"identifier":"why-should-i-care-whether-im-being-a-good-citizen-in-the-open-community","label":"Why should I care whether I’m being a “good citizen in the open community”?","html_id":"why-should-i-care-whether-im-being-a-good-citizen-in-the-open-community","implicit":true,"key":"O6l2HtQorS"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":28,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Organizations are driven by incentives, and ultimately if a behavior isn’t conducive\nto the organization’s bottom-line, then we can’t expect them to adopt that behavior.\nI’d argue that interacting with the open community has a number of bottom-line benefits, here are a few:","position":{"start":{"line":26,"column":1},"end":{"line":26,"column":1}},"key":"LiTLqAp4ii"}],"key":"HsW63qJ1st"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It makes you a more attractive place to work","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"mRv3V4C6WR"}],"key":"Jl537SaS1i"},{"type":"text","value":". Operating in open communities is\noften where people learn their technical skills, and while people come and go through\norganizations, the open community remains. Employees want to interact in these communities,\nand employers that have a good relationship with open communities are more attractive\nplaces to work.","position":{"start":{"line":30,"column":1},"end":{"line":30,"column":1}},"key":"f7HTkpVMjA"}],"key":"vZrqqLDSf9"}],"key":"nwO9E8WkiP"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":38,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open communities can be a great training resource","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"sxpPBN8bbr"}],"key":"ENKvf8OPCT"},{"type":"text","value":". Have some improvements to make in\nyour Python or R skills? Need to tool-up on your ability to write CI/CD pipelines? Open\ncommunities are a great place to get feedback and guidance from others with more experience.\nThe open community is a resource for constantly tooling-up your technical skills. Use it!","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"J2uet6srFn"}],"key":"h5esOFCqIT"}],"key":"m5V8I1CncE"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":42,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open communities can make better team-members","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"key":"j8JWaeBPDA"}],"key":"DbYF33CfI3"},{"type":"text","value":". Making complex technical/social decisions\nwith a diverse community distributed across the world is really difficult! For the communities\nthat do this well, interacting with them can be a fantastic learning experience in team-work,\ncommunication, coalition-building, critical feedback, and leadership.","position":{"start":{"line":39,"column":1},"end":{"line":39,"column":1}},"key":"XrHWJskMTP"}],"key":"c4eSU4yhya"}],"key":"b4TgtjMFgi"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interacting with open communities gives you influence","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"CE58b98Aqg"}],"key":"IdJG5Ni1TN"},{"type":"text","value":". If you’re using an open\ntool, don’t you want to have a say in how that tool grows and evolves? Being a passive consumer\nof open technology means you’re at the whim of that community’s wishes. If you’re a ","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"UeKmoyFt5v"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"part","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"qr3iThDgFC"}],"key":"yU6cKDA8xf"},{"type":"text","value":" of\nthat community, you can influence its direction to align with your organization’s goals.","position":{"start":{"line":43,"column":1},"end":{"line":43,"column":1}},"key":"oosP8QINGA"}],"key":"yBrqM4XGgG"}],"key":"kTHpFLRGsp"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":51,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interacting with open communities means you write less code","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"G9Ne6zrQ9v"}],"key":"TJPUrcm89m"},{"type":"text","value":". I suspect that in the long-term,\nwriting your own code will almost cost more than using somebody else’s code (in terms of\nperson-hours it requires). If you’ve got a say in an open project, you minimize the chance that\nyou must either maintain an internal fork w/ significant changes, or create your own new thing\nthat you must now maintain on your own.","position":{"start":{"line":47,"column":1},"end":{"line":47,"column":1}},"key":"MZ2to8oFlL"}],"key":"GNg7H79OS6"}],"key":"J5tP86xBKD"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":58,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Interacting with open communities can make them more robust","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"key":"vyDaeVyrqf"}],"key":"JO0agrQMuh"},{"type":"text","value":". Finally, let’s not forget\nthat communities can and do fail all the time. What happens if a project you depend on\nstops making bug fixes? Or doesn’t have bandwidth to maintain security patches? By contributing\nresources to these communities, we keep them thriving and healthy creators of open-source\ntools. We all benefit from this, and more importantly you don’t have a dead project that your\ncore product or teams depend on.","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1},"end":{"line":52,"column":1}},"key":"gVls1A0N5a"}],"key":"Aadqf4OxyT"}],"key":"tupfeBrGEz"}],"key":"TgWomfwmIA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":62,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Those are just a few benefits, but I’m sure there are others. For more information and ideas about\nhow open source communities can be a benefit to your organization, I recommend Mozilla’s\n","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"CKYA0JAx2I"},{"type":"link","url":"https://blog.mozilla.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/MZOTS_OS_Archetypes_report_ext_scr.pdf","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open Source Archetypes","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"MGMJSylely"}],"urlSource":"https://blog.mozilla.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/MZOTS_OS_Archetypes_report_ext_scr.pdf","key":"TcPt3VVuMy"},{"type":"text","value":"\nresearch paper.","position":{"start":{"line":59,"column":1},"end":{"line":59,"column":1}},"key":"ZN5uUm0xOH"}],"key":"cjBMgTDgLC"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":66,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Now that we’ve got that out\nof the way, let’s move on to deciding whether or not your organization is, in fact, being\na positive actor in the open-source community.","position":{"start":{"line":64,"column":1},"end":{"line":64,"column":1}},"key":"Ts3BQIE7UG"}],"key":"DWWJRBnep2"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can I tell if my organization is not being a good citizen in the open community?","position":{"start":{"line":68,"column":1},"end":{"line":68,"column":1}},"key":"UmdhDx4mrP"}],"identifier":"how-can-i-tell-if-my-organization-is-not-being-a-good-citizen-in-the-open-community","label":"How can I tell if my organization is not being a good citizen in the open community?","html_id":"how-can-i-tell-if-my-organization-is-not-being-a-good-citizen-in-the-open-community","implicit":true,"key":"Dj2ZEIGx8O"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":72,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"I suspect that many organizations simply haven’t put a ton of thought into whether they’ve got a positive-or-negative\nrelationship with the open communities that intersect with their work. Here’s a quick set of questions\nto ask yourself:","position":{"start":{"line":70,"column":1},"end":{"line":70,"column":1}},"key":"qrlCrVEosl"}],"key":"ijk1XnGO6Y"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":77,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do your employees routinely use open-source software in their work?","position":{"start":{"line":74,"column":1},"end":{"line":74,"column":1}},"key":"WBL0ulh9ij"}],"key":"gpDMytgvoJ"}],"key":"W155S0gmVK"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Does your organization create a product that depends on open-source software?","position":{"start":{"line":75,"column":1},"end":{"line":75,"column":1}},"key":"nIdmwiFyha"}],"key":"vnpMCGiD7r"}],"key":"IR8C4nENWY"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":77,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Does your organization depend on proprietary software that depends on open-source software?","position":{"start":{"line":76,"column":1},"end":{"line":76,"column":1}},"key":"zV416zsIhz"}],"key":"BxqlxGkC6v"}],"key":"dR6g9H6SxO"}],"key":"OYlptzVoZ3"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":78,"column":1},"end":{"line":78,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you answered “yes” to any of those questions, then ask yourself the following questions:","position":{"start":{"line":78,"column":1},"end":{"line":78,"column":1}},"key":"CjziaMVe8Q"}],"key":"nYL8SwZCVe"},{"type":"list","ordered":false,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":85,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do you have explicit policies that encourage employees to contribute back to open projects?","position":{"start":{"line":80,"column":1},"end":{"line":80,"column":1}},"key":"n68aQzKOzG"}],"key":"mGOLAaM6zv"}],"key":"uTuba9FjDJ"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":81,"column":1},"end":{"line":81,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do you have explicit funding mechanisms to give resources to open projects?","position":{"start":{"line":81,"column":1},"end":{"line":81,"column":1}},"key":"N3TaCRLbBs"}],"key":"ZrCyJQLWVy"}],"key":"SYrboUUHpt"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do you explicitly call out and acknowledge the importance of those open tools in your presentations and (some kinds of) marketing?","position":{"start":{"line":82,"column":1},"end":{"line":82,"column":1}},"key":"J7MgjEt5bG"}],"key":"J3etf8lpn6"}],"key":"MgucXFefOk"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":83,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do you have regular, open channels of communication with those open communities?","position":{"start":{"line":83,"column":1},"end":{"line":83,"column":1}},"key":"i1S7bUNYlE"}],"key":"F1hrSFYYT1"}],"key":"JVuuc7v8dQ"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":85,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Do these behaviors scale with the amount of value you derive from open communities?","position":{"start":{"line":84,"column":1},"end":{"line":84,"column":1}},"key":"xvbSnhXqgT"}],"key":"fWa8Ev8Cpd"}],"key":"B8ejSH9x5Z"}],"key":"Tf2bteTiBh"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":87,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you answered “no” to these questions, then you’re probably exploiting the open community.\nYou should stop that!","position":{"start":{"line":86,"column":1},"end":{"line":86,"column":1}},"key":"f8eaZcNR7o"}],"key":"iI9MMGyyp6"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":92,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"However, avoiding this kind of one-way relationship with the open source community is complex\nand requires some new efforts and thinking from both sides of the equation.\nThe rest of this post includes a few ideas on how open projects, as well as organizations,\ncan improve this relationship.","position":{"start":{"line":89,"column":1},"end":{"line":89,"column":1}},"key":"ZDXV5Imw3B"}],"key":"DhfanFcoNG"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can open communities encourage organizations to be good citizens","position":{"start":{"line":94,"column":1},"end":{"line":94,"column":1}},"key":"BQP5CUQ1rr"}],"identifier":"how-can-open-communities-encourage-organizations-to-be-good-citizens","label":"How can open communities encourage organizations to be good citizens","html_id":"how-can-open-communities-encourage-organizations-to-be-good-citizens","implicit":true,"key":"qyJ4429zqA"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":97,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"How can the open community encourage better interactions\nwith organizations that depend on our tools?","position":{"start":{"line":96,"column":1},"end":{"line":96,"column":1}},"key":"mqLzZIM5r4"}],"key":"PjnyYgCSlT"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":103,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"First off, I think these are ","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"dzA8QbQhDq"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"not","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"Z99IDqE0Zv"}],"key":"wlzH2tbE5b"},{"type":"text","value":" problems that we should have to solve with licensing [1]\n. These are ","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"GmgiSqWdVu"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"social","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"cvZnrp1oqj"}],"key":"XaYzfBFaDD"},{"type":"text","value":", ","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"HwF1IvAuie"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"moral","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"zebSVXSSXO"}],"key":"MEL55EUvCp"},{"type":"text","value":", and ","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"aN0ICS00Fc"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"incentives","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"tasKf9jni8"}],"key":"rtBpJd5O0v"},{"type":"text","value":" problems.\nThere are plenty of organizations that make money from open-source, but that still\nmanage to spend time being part of the communities that they draw value from. How do we encourage this\nkind of behavior? I have a few ideas, but we should spend more time thinking about this:","position":{"start":{"line":99,"column":1},"end":{"line":99,"column":1}},"key":"Z3DUjxzi2W"}],"key":"NiSk6podB2"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":110,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":109,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open communities need more ways to signal “thank you” to organization that behave well","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"key":"XkFfL6UzjM"}],"key":"nn1z1yoGaD"},{"type":"text","value":". For\nexample, the Kubernetes community runs a ","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"key":"KwBCu7YUUt"},{"type":"link","url":"http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=kubernetes-group&metric=commits","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"service called stackalytics","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"key":"DKuwl6ndNE"}],"urlSource":"http://stackalytics.com/?project_type=kubernetes-group&metric=commits","key":"oPJLL7q5bY"},{"type":"text","value":"\nthat lists contributions broken down by company. It would be great to adapt this kind of visualization\nfor the broader OSS community. More generally, \"thank-you\"s should be for specific behavior, and it should be clear whether that behavior is a one-off or is on-going. Organizations are incentive-driven, so we should create more\npositive incentives for them to interact.","position":{"start":{"line":105,"column":1},"end":{"line":105,"column":1}},"key":"nOFTVYKkpI"}],"key":"qKx7uEayg0"}],"key":"Ow0uwDS32s"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":115,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open communities need a better vocabulary to describe bad behavior when it exists","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"pvmeotRIWO"}],"key":"s17ZNxbXEs"},{"type":"text","value":". I’ve had\na number of conversations with folks that are frustrated when an organization uses their tool without\ngiving back. These people often feel like there is no medium through which they can “call-out” the\noffending organization without sounding “whiny”, and so they internalize this stress. If there were a way to\nquickly describe what this behavior is, it could be easier for people to call it when they see it.","position":{"start":{"line":111,"column":1},"end":{"line":111,"column":1}},"key":"n8ksSt2zGn"}],"key":"L0A047WKXW"}],"key":"rGpOO5ktPx"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":120,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Open communities need to make it clear ","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"Hwg1cQdLYL"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"how","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"XedPaxDFFh"}],"key":"Dp1nt1y0mT"},{"type":"text","value":" organizations can get involved","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"zXOBAQ0jL8"}],"key":"G6RxLJizlH"},{"type":"text","value":". This is a two-way street.\nWhile we need more participation from organizations making products or services around open-source, we also\nneed to position our open communities so that there are clear pathways for interaction and contribution.\nThings like roadmaps, clear community governance, and well-tuned practices around encouraging outsiders to\njoin the community would go a long way.","position":{"start":{"line":116,"column":1},"end":{"line":116,"column":1}},"key":"RSaBodut97"}],"key":"FcTpohmlXD"}],"key":"QYEzt6lJmT"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":128,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":127,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Funding bodies should consider open-source participation when giving out money","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"key":"pulezLojuc"}],"key":"oSHxdA1sLS"},{"type":"text","value":". Perhaps this one only\napplies to some sub-fields, but private philanthropies or public funding bodies (like the NSF) should consider\na project’s intersection with the pre-existing open community when deciding whether to fund a project.\nIf you propose creating a new tool, you should be required to do due-diligence on other tools in that space,\nand explain why you won’t just contribute to those communities instead of building your own. If you propose\nbuilding a product off of open-source software, you should have a plan for how you’ll contribute back to those\ncommunities. Saying that you’ll open-source your code and throw it over the wall is ","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"key":"qvZUJtJpDy"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"not enough","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"key":"q6FojrmGmn"}],"key":"R9WllDGlJ5"},{"type":"text","value":".","position":{"start":{"line":121,"column":1},"end":{"line":121,"column":1}},"key":"BGbGz81OZ4"}],"key":"EYxABDPuEI"}],"key":"x8ZezJWQHT"}],"key":"ohP18aeVCu"},{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What could organizations do now to support open communities?","position":{"start":{"line":129,"column":1},"end":{"line":129,"column":1}},"key":"ObJWpdYl10"}],"identifier":"what-could-organizations-do-now-to-support-open-communities","label":"What could organizations do now to support open communities?","html_id":"what-could-organizations-do-now-to-support-open-communities","implicit":true,"key":"KPgx9y6225"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":131,"column":1},"end":{"line":133,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"All of the steps above are fairly long-term solutions to a problem that exists right now. What are some things\nthat organizations can do now in order to make sure they’re perceived as more positive actors in open communities?\nHere’s a short “off the top of my head” list.","position":{"start":{"line":131,"column":1},"end":{"line":131,"column":1}},"key":"nK1uKCAXZV"}],"key":"bVohPec2WK"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":150,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":136,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you’re an employee, find allies and ","position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":135,"column":1}},"key":"ijkmS1gBW3"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":135,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pressure management to support open-source software","position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":135,"column":1}},"key":"caPMYgHdWR"}],"key":"fLw86rZEqt"},{"type":"text","value":". Often, organizations\ncontribute to open source only because employees make a case for it.","position":{"start":{"line":135,"column":1},"end":{"line":135,"column":1}},"key":"eXt8916kVe"}],"key":"nkicTasYzu"}],"key":"AVL1ORPXol"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":137,"column":1},"end":{"line":139,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you’re at management-level, ","position":{"start":{"line":137,"column":1},"end":{"line":137,"column":1}},"key":"xkPjvMaDFQ"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":137,"column":1},"end":{"line":137,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"create space for your employees to contribute to open-source software","position":{"start":{"line":137,"column":1},"end":{"line":137,"column":1}},"key":"pooRYkWAWT"}],"key":"w4ypx43mxw"},{"type":"text","value":". They’ll\nbe happier employees (OSS is a gratifying experience), you’ll have more say in the tools you use, and you’ll be\na more attractive place to work for developers.","position":{"start":{"line":137,"column":1},"end":{"line":137,"column":1}},"key":"jFSHAmIcpV"}],"key":"Zt95tpFRIb"}],"key":"eoe3GFKSwZ"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":140,"column":1},"end":{"line":142,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you’re at the executive / strategic level, ","position":{"start":{"line":140,"column":1},"end":{"line":140,"column":1}},"key":"vtTK7AsfFl"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":140,"column":1},"end":{"line":140,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"incorporate an open-source strategy in your business plan","position":{"start":{"line":140,"column":1},"end":{"line":140,"column":1}},"key":"PeRIAPVBG9"}],"key":"EHqsLiIf5f"},{"type":"text","value":". Open source\ncan be an incredible resource if harnessed properly. Your organization will be better off in the long term if you treat\nopen communities as partners rather than sources of free labor.","position":{"start":{"line":140,"column":1},"end":{"line":140,"column":1}},"key":"ORIh0TwRbb"}],"key":"ciVwlqjSwi"}],"key":"nVChH8RIZI"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":143,"column":1},"end":{"line":145,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you’re creating a new open-source tool, ","position":{"start":{"line":143,"column":1},"end":{"line":143,"column":1}},"key":"d20xgp1Or5"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":143,"column":1},"end":{"line":143,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"write a justification for why you’re creating a new thing, instead of contributing to an existing thing","position":{"start":{"line":143,"column":1},"end":{"line":143,"column":1}},"key":"nYl7wWmt7t"}],"key":"guy1GPC4Vg"},{"type":"text","value":".\nSometimes there’s a great reason not to jump on-board with a pre-existing tool. However, you need to signal that you’ve\nthought hard about this, and recognize the downside to creating yet-another open source tool when alternatives exist.","position":{"start":{"line":143,"column":1},"end":{"line":143,"column":1}},"key":"MlFNKddmCI"}],"key":"l1pMg9UUzy"}],"key":"kOzzy9BU4N"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":146,"column":1},"end":{"line":148,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"If you’ve got a product that directly uses open-source, ","position":{"start":{"line":146,"column":1},"end":{"line":146,"column":1}},"key":"R4nFVEMEgk"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":146,"column":1},"end":{"line":146,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"have an open-source plan for giving back","position":{"start":{"line":146,"column":1},"end":{"line":146,"column":1}},"key":"QlO2a8GwoM"}],"key":"tmzVu9oohP"},{"type":"text","value":". Signal to the\ncommunity what you’re doing to say “thank you” for all of the value you’re getting from the open community. Maybe it’s\npeople’s time to contribute back, maybe it’s money, maybe it’s marketing for OSS communities.","position":{"start":{"line":146,"column":1},"end":{"line":146,"column":1}},"key":"nDbdEOV3zf"}],"key":"JYsGVDkrWx"}],"key":"q54rnGraTU"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":150,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Write an annual “contributing back to open source” report","position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"key":"ax3gerkFrV"}],"key":"X8R1uqfYXa"},{"type":"text","value":" that details the ways you’ve contributed back. It’ll highlight your organization’s role as a leader in this space, and signal the value that these tools provide for you.","position":{"start":{"line":149,"column":1},"end":{"line":149,"column":1}},"key":"Jbmf2D4QUf"}],"key":"Y2QLdSgl1X"}],"key":"gXUFFOgQ2X"}],"key":"JzeXsGMySI"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":151,"column":1},"end":{"line":151,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"That’s it for now, though as you can probably tell, this is a complex topic with a lot of nuance. If you’ve got any thoughts of your own, feel free to leave a comment below, or ","position":{"start":{"line":151,"column":1},"end":{"line":151,"column":1}},"key":"pm5DYJkDQM"},{"type":"link","url":"https://twitter.com/choldgraf","position":{"start":{"line":151,"column":1},"end":{"line":151,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"reach out to me on twitter","position":{"start":{"line":151,"column":1},"end":{"line":151,"column":1}},"key":"UT5wybj5cQ"}],"urlSource":"https://twitter.com/choldgraf","key":"BbmlMxrg3t"}],"key":"eRT3rKoiTK"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":154,"column":1},"end":{"line":154,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":154,"column":1},"end":{"line":154,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"[1] A note on licenses","position":{"start":{"line":154,"column":1},"end":{"line":154,"column":1}},"key":"MEFs3YZLjy"}],"key":"lcvYE1laWe"}],"key":"EfgCoY8nvn"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":156,"column":1},"end":{"line":161,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When I talk about this stuff, people often mention ","position":{"start":{"line":156,"column":1},"end":{"line":156,"column":1}},"key":"W2FPnDD4NB"},{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":156,"column":1},"end":{"line":156,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"copyleft","position":{"start":{"line":156,"column":1},"end":{"line":156,"column":1}},"